Great Train Robbery","startTime":null,"eventDescription":""Joshua Powell and the Great Train Robbery" may not fit on a marquis, but the name suits the band just fine. Joshua and his folk band borrowed their brand from a 1903 silent Western and have crafted their sound in that sure-footed Americana tradition ever since. The crux of their music is in the storytelling – stories that embrace the fact that we are all human together. The band has two new releases: The Commonwealth EP, available for free on Noise Trade, and a new LP, Man Is Born For Trouble, available in April from digital outlets.

The band may have originated in the heartland, but there is something distinctly Southern about their songs. There is dusty peacefulness in the lulling folk that evokes comparisons to Iron and Wine and Fionn Regan, and an unmistakable grit that erupts like a bar fight when the band delves into their rockier side. Joshua and the band spent nearly two years in Indiana perfecting this duality as they played every Midwest bar and coffeehouse that would have them.

Their self-produced debut EP, We All Say Hello, enjoyed immense exposure and success on Noise Trade in 2011, sharing the chart with acts like The Civil Wars and Young the Giant. They subsequently released their first full length, Traveler, which Stereo Subversion heralded as having "diverse harmonies" and "immense depth."

Johnson","startTime":null,"eventDescription":""WHERE TO BEGIN WHEN THE BEGINNING'S BLOWN?"
An iconic opening line to an album is something all songwriters strive for. Chicago troubadour Jesse W. Johnson's new single, "Primal Scream," the first track from an EP of the same name, flies high off the bat, and the world-weary delivery and fuzzed-out guitars ensure the rest of the song sticks the landing.

Johnson is a veteran of the Chicago scene, having reached local acclaim fronting Jet W. Lee, and his experience is immediately apparent upon first listen. Having recruited former Jet W. Lee bassist Paul Doerr and former cohorts (and current Hemmingbirds members) Zach Benkowski and Yoo Soo Kim on drums and viola/organ/vocals respectively, the Primal Scream two-song 7"/five-song digital EP presents tight, muscular songcraft with beautiful melodies and surprisingly dark lyrics. And this juxtaposition is no accident.

"I love dark music and I love even more music that sounds upbeat but has a melancholy lyric," Johnson says. "I'm mainly influenced by Emily Haines, Neil Young, Nick Cave, and David Bazan. With this EP, I think I've been able to mix these into something of my own, probably better than I ever have before."

Indeed, "Fucked Up First" is a barroom brawler that evokes Nick Cave at his most depressingly debauched (or perhaps Cursive's Tim Kasher at his most debauchedly depressed). "Why Aren't We In L.A.?" makes beautiful use of Kim's haunting viola, creating an atmosphere of melancholy in sharp contrast to Johnson's radio-ready melody, perhaps a nod to his unabashed admiration for current pop royalty like Tove Lo and Taylor Swift.

But it's the EP's fourth track, "Springfield Supportive Living," that will most increase the distance between jaws and eyebrows. A swampy stomp courtesy of Doerr and Benkowski's powerful rhythmic chemistry gives way to an enormous chorus, building to a raucous guitar solo that would do the aforementioned Mr. Young proud. "I'm out of it," Johnson sings as the song builds to its ending, his voice losing coherence with each repetition. The gentle closer, "Expecting To Fall," is a beautiful slice of Americana, just Johnson's delicate vocal and a guitar, eventually joined by viola to great effect. When the rest of the band joins for a massive crescendo, the build is so natural and seamless, it's easy to forget they're there at all.

Ultimately though, the record is as much a product of the chemistry of the musicians as the quality of the songs. "Paul has been a huge inspiration to keep going, he's really one of my best friends," Johnson mentions. "Yoo Soo and Zach were in a band called Post Historic with me back in Champaign, IL forever ago. We've been playing music together for 10 years now, and whenever we get together, it's really something special."
